00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:25.930
But then also from just a
best practices standpoint,

00:09:25.930 --> 00:09:28.740
how do you let your
creativity flow?

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:31.680
And we've got some advice from
some of the leading creativity

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:35.000
experts in the world talking
about how to make that happen.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.650
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Yeah,
so don't downplay that.

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:40.826
I think one of the things that
got me excited about "Culinary

00:09:40.826 --> 00:09:42.450
Artistry" when I
looked at it years ago

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:46.110
was the pedigree of chefs
you have in your back pocket.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.080
I'm interested to
hear how you informed

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:51.210
some of the initial
relationships with these chefs.

00:09:51.210 --> 00:09:53.290
You're talking about
every top chef out there.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:56.610
Whether it's Danko, Ripert,
Danny Meyers, restaurateur,

00:09:56.610 --> 00:10:00.180
you've got amazing chefs
that are taking their time

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:02.700
to share some of their
most intimate secrets

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:05.080
on what's made them successful.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:08.010
And I don't take that lightly,
and none of our chefs at Google

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:10.560
that do such an amazing
job in bringing the food

00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:12.605
program to life here do either.

00:10:12.605 --> 00:10:13.980
These are the
inspirational chefs

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:16.260
that they look to aspire to be.

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:17.760
What were some of the initial--

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:18.750
how did that happen?

00:10:18.750 --> 00:10:20.750
What was that first chef
that you were like, oh,

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:22.574
my god, if I could
just get this one to--

00:10:22.574 --> 00:10:23.490
how did that go about?

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:24.630
KAREN PAGE: Well, you
know, when we started out,

00:10:24.630 --> 00:10:26.070
we'd never written
a book before.

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:28.140
And so how do you get
the world's best chefs

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:28.780
to talk to you?

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:29.696
We didn't really know.

00:10:29.696 --> 00:10:31.620
But the ace in our
hole was that Andrew

00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:34.110
was working as a
professional chef in Boston,

00:10:34.110 --> 00:10:36.300
and he was working with
Chris Schlesinger and Lydia

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:38.091
Shire, who at the time
were two of the best

00:10:38.091 --> 00:10:40.470
chefs in the country, who
happened to be in Boston.

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:43.060
And so having-- starting
out with the two of them,

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:46.336
and then he went on to work
with Anne Rosenzweig at Arcadia

00:10:46.336 --> 00:10:47.691
in New York City.

00:10:47.691 --> 00:10:49.690
And once we had the three
of them in our pocket,

00:10:49.690 --> 00:10:50.940
we could kind of go to people.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:52.380
Because there was
three big names

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:54.660
that they knew us
personally that

00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:56.880
had some belief that we
could actually write a book.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:59.296
And so they thought, well, if
Lydia's in, and Chris is in,

00:10:59.296 --> 00:11:01.150
and Anne's in, then I'm in, too.

00:11:01.150 --> 00:11:03.150
So from there, we went
to other top chefs

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:04.800
in Boston and New York.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:07.860
Then we were doing the research
on weekends and evenings.

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:10.822
We would travel to San Francisco
and knock on Gary Danko's door.

00:11:10.822 --> 00:11:13.280
Actually, you had also worked
with Madeleine at that point.

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:14.170
ANDREW DORNENBURG: I worked
with Madeleine Kamman

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:17.640
up at the School for American
Chefs at Beringer Vineyards.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.090
And so we met Gary Danko.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:22.410
We met other chefs
through her, too.

00:11:22.410 --> 00:11:25.495
But the key is Karen
writes a great letter.

00:11:25.495 --> 00:11:26.370
That's how you do it.

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:28.200
She goes, well, we've just
interviewed these other people.

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:30.180
Would you like to be
included in our new book?

00:11:30.180 --> 00:11:32.846
And even though they didn't know
us, they knew the other people.

00:11:32.846 --> 00:11:35.550
And it's like-- and also,
asking for 15 minutes.

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:37.080
We only need 15, 20 minutes.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:39.990
And that always, almost
always, turned into an hour.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:43.270
And I'll never forget we
interviewed Chef Barbara

00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:46.110
Tropp, a legendary restaurateur
and chef, China Moon

00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:48.060
Cafe in San Francisco.

00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:50.980
And at the end-- we talked for
almost an hour and a half--

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:53.580
she goes, I've never had
a conversation like this.

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:55.650
And we're like, neither have we.

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.560
And then she's like, try not
to edit my words too much.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:00.521
We're like, you
went to Princeton.

00:12:00.521 --> 00:12:01.020
You're good.

00:12:03.584 --> 00:12:06.062
KAREN PAGE: PhD in
Chinese poetics.

00:12:06.062 --> 00:12:07.450
She spoke in poetry.

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:10.300
Just an amazing woman,
founder of the Women Chefs

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:11.980
and Restaurateurs
Association that we

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:14.410
talked about was near and
dear to Dede and myself,

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:16.000
as a former board
member of that.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.280
So I think once you
kind of get started,

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:20.610
then it is easier to
get the ball rolling.

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:23.430
And that's true of any
aspect of creativity.

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:27.900
The Goethe quote, it's like,
whatever you can imagine--

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:31.040
and I won't get the words
right, but you know, be bold.

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:31.870
Take action.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:34.330
And then it really
has a magic to it

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:35.590
that really starts to unfold.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:37.660
So once you take action
in a certain direction--

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:40.625
we talk in the book-- there's
an A to Z section of the book,

00:12:40.625 --> 00:12:41.500
the back of the book.

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:43.060
That is laid out
like "Flavor Bible,"

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:44.601
if any of you are
familiar with that,

00:12:44.601 --> 00:12:46.810
where it's a three-column
format, A to Z.

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:47.950
But instead of flavors--

00:12:47.950 --> 00:12:50.500
we have apples to zucchini
in "The Flavor Bible"--

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:55.452
we have every other topic under
the sun, from architecture to--

00:12:55.452 --> 00:12:57.160
ANDREW DORNENBURG:
"Alice in Wonderland."

00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:57.985
KAREN PAGE: "Alice
in Wonderland."

00:12:57.985 --> 00:12:59.610
ANDREW DORNENBURG:
And there's actually

00:12:59.610 --> 00:13:02.110
a restaurant based on "Alice
in Wonderland," the book.

00:13:02.110 --> 00:13:05.260
And we actually
finish up with yoga.

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:08.150
Rick Bayless of the Frontera
Grill and Topolobampo,

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:10.400
the restaurant of the year
and the James Beard Award--

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.281
he's been doing
yoga for 20 years.

00:13:12.281 --> 00:13:13.780
And this is what's
fun about knowing

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:14.821
these people for so long.

00:13:14.821 --> 00:13:17.950
It's like, hey, Rick, would you
mind doing a yoga pose for us?

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:19.380
So he's in a chef's jacket.

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:22.421
And he just pops up on the
counter and does yoga for us.

00:13:22.421 --> 00:13:23.170
And so it's like--

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:23.665
KAREN PAGE: He's amazing.

00:13:23.665 --> 00:13:24.220
ANDREW DORNENBURG:
He's like, sure.

00:13:24.220 --> 00:13:25.150
KAREN PAGE: For as long
as we've known him--

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:27.566
because we interviewed Rick
Bayless for all of our books--

00:13:27.566 --> 00:13:30.220
we had never seen him do
this amazing pose before.

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:32.830
But you know, anyone as
multi-talented as Rick,

00:13:32.830 --> 00:13:36.930
who has been doing yoga for
20 years, it's pretty awesome.

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:39.310
So what an inspiration
to talk to chefs.

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:41.094
And again, you know,
when you're talking

00:13:41.094 --> 00:13:43.510
to chefs for your 11th book
as opposed to your first book,

00:13:43.510 --> 00:13:46.060
it's a whole different
ballgame, because you built up

00:13:46.060 --> 00:13:48.520
a certain level of
knowledge and trust.

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:51.280
And so we're talking to people
about what inspires them,

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:53.580
and they went a little,
you know, rogue with us.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:54.050
ANDREW DORNENBURG:
They went there.

00:13:54.050 --> 00:13:55.216
KAREN PAGE: They went there.

00:13:55.216 --> 00:13:57.410
And they could tell
us quite honestly,

00:13:57.410 --> 00:13:59.200
you know, I look
at my ingredients.

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:00.460
I talk to my ingredients.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:02.650
And so I'll take an
apple, and I'll put it

00:14:02.650 --> 00:14:04.219
in the center of the table.

00:14:04.219 --> 00:14:06.010
And I'll have a
conversation with the apple

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:08.509
and say, OK, apple, what
are we going to do today?

00:14:08.509 --> 00:14:10.300
You've done some
interesting things before,

00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:11.716
but what are we
going to do today?

00:14:11.716 --> 00:14:14.170
And there is this
level of intuition.

00:14:14.170 --> 00:14:16.540
You could call it
mediumship, channeling,

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:19.120
whatever you want to call
it, that takes place.

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:22.440
And we're talking about the most
respected chefs in the country.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:25.090
So Jose Andres, based
in Washington, DC,

00:14:25.090 --> 00:14:26.380
will talk to his ingredients.

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:28.088
He said, if you talk
to your ingredients,

00:14:28.088 --> 00:14:29.770
they will always
tell you a story.

00:14:29.770 --> 00:14:32.440
You just have to have your
ears open to hear that story.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.200
Ghaya Oliveira, who just won
the James Beard Award this year,

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:38.639
is the best outstanding pastry
chef in the United States.

00:14:38.639 --> 00:14:40.930
She's the one who puts the
apple on the parchment paper

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:43.055
in the center of Restaurant
Daniel in New York City

00:14:43.055 --> 00:14:45.340
and says, talk to me, apple.

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:47.880
Phillip Foss from EL
Ideas in Chicago--

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:48.880
ANDREW DORNENBURG: Yeah.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:50.270
Phillip Foss, he's great.

00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:52.900
This is a very
fascinating restaurant.

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:55.120
It's in a loft way out
in the middle of nowhere.

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:56.830
They say take a car.

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:59.200
You know, don't take
public transportation.

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:02.350
But he will say, the
ingredient is my child.

00:15:02.350 --> 00:15:05.530
And I want my child to
succeed and be happy.

00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:09.200
And it's up to me to
care for the child

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:11.285
and make sure it's
physically, emotionally,

00:15:11.285 --> 00:15:13.240
and mentally, and
spiritually happy.

00:15:13.240 --> 00:15:15.670
So he treats his ingredients
like they're children

00:15:15.670 --> 00:15:18.040
and raises them and, again,
has that conversation.

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:22.030
And he has the craziest
menu I think I've ever seen.

00:15:22.030 --> 00:15:24.370
He will do a menu
based on the '80s.

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:28.270
He will produce a dish and
play a certain piece of music

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:29.657
that it's inspired by.

00:15:29.657 --> 00:15:31.240
KAREN PAGE: Madonna's
"Like A Virgin,"

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:33.400
he's got a little
dish to go with that.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:36.520
He'll serve "cocaine,"
which is basically

00:15:36.520 --> 00:15:40.302
a lime and coconut powder on
a mirror with a razor blade,

00:15:40.302 --> 00:15:41.760
at his Michelin-starred
restaurant.

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:43.210
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: I think
our chefs are getting inspired.

00:15:43.210 --> 00:15:44.690
I hear them giggling.

00:15:44.690 --> 00:15:45.940
KAREN PAGE: He's out there.

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:47.981
But he's got a Michelin
star, and he's respected.

00:15:47.981 --> 00:15:48.970
He's so celebrated.

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:50.680
And so, you know,
there are chefs out

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:52.030
there who are creative.

00:15:52.030 --> 00:15:53.350
They're pushing the envelope.

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:55.450
And they're doing a lot of
things that are a lot of fun.

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.866
And you might not serve exactly
the same things in a home,

00:15:57.866 --> 00:16:01.270
but you can be inspired
by the thought process.

00:16:01.270 --> 00:16:05.320
He does a dish of Frosties
and french fries, which

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:06.710
was inspired by his daughters.

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:09.224
Was a single dad for a
while and raising his kids,

00:16:09.224 --> 00:16:11.140
and the babysitter took
them to Wendy's, where

00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:13.000
they learned to dip their--
did anybody do that?

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:14.240
Dip their french
fries in the Frosty?

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:14.770
ANDREW DORNENBURG: I'd
never heard of that, yeah.

00:16:14.770 --> 00:16:16.210
KAREN PAGE: Did you ever
have it in a Michelin starred

00:16:16.210 --> 00:16:16.709
restaurant?

00:16:16.709 --> 00:16:18.910
If you go to EL
Ideas in Chicago,

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:20.680
you can taste it there.

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:23.560
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: So what
I love about these books,

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:25.870
again, is that it caters
to a variety of audiences.

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:27.661
You've got people that
are cooking at home.

00:16:27.661 --> 00:16:29.697
You've got people that
are beginning to cook

00:16:29.697 --> 00:16:30.530
or learning to cook.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:32.650
Or you've got people that have
been cooking for many years.

00:16:32.650 --> 00:16:34.030
What I love about
this, in essence,

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:35.946
is that it's very similar
to our program here.

00:16:35.946 --> 00:16:38.452
We're really trying to enable
people to pick up skills

00:16:38.452 --> 00:16:39.660
and give them the confidence.

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:41.620
And when you dive
into the book, you're

00:16:41.620 --> 00:16:43.120
going to see that
the quotes in here

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:45.670
are not only from some of
the biggest and baddest names

00:16:45.670 --> 00:16:48.040
out there, but they're the
really great tidbits that

00:16:48.040 --> 00:16:50.020
really help unpack
what they're thinking

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:51.320
and their thought process.

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:53.260
So let's think-- let's talk
a little bit about the book.

00:16:53.260 --> 00:16:54.593
So the book is very interesting.

00:16:54.593 --> 00:16:56.600
This is a book of no recipes.

00:16:56.600 --> 00:16:57.590
This is a book--

00:16:57.590 --> 00:17:00.220
and thank you, because there's
a lot of recipes out there--

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:03.490
but it's really around
a few different aspects.

00:17:03.490 --> 00:17:05.050
So you start the
book around mastery.

00:17:05.050 --> 00:17:06.675
And so there's a
section on that, which

00:17:06.675 --> 00:17:08.467
I'd love to talk about briefly.

00:17:08.467 --> 00:17:10.300
And then section two
is more around alchemy,

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:11.464
the transformation stage.

00:17:11.464 --> 00:17:13.130
And then number three
is around, really,

00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:16.332
that creativity aspect, which
obviously is the bulk of it.

00:17:16.332 --> 00:17:18.290
Can you talk about the
three different sections

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:20.810
briefly so we can kind of
get an understanding of why

00:17:20.810 --> 00:17:23.060
you went that direction?

00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:25.230
And then we'll bring
in some examples.

00:17:25.230 --> 00:17:26.120
KAREN PAGE: Sure.

00:17:26.120 --> 00:17:28.387
Well, we start out with
mastery, because, as Picasso

00:17:28.387 --> 00:17:30.470
lets us know, you can't
break the rules unless you

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:31.680
know what the rules are.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:33.800
So you start out by
understanding the rules.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:35.780
And the way to do that
is really to learn

00:17:35.780 --> 00:17:40.110
to think like a chef, shop like
a chef, and season like a chef.

00:17:40.110 --> 00:17:41.880
And so in terms of
thinking like a chef,

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:44.960
we have done lots of
research on the leading books

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:47.166
that chefs everywhere
say that you

00:17:47.166 --> 00:17:49.040
should have in your
culinary library at home.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:51.630
And we've narrowed it
down to the 20 top books.

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:53.469
And if you read these
books, if you really

00:17:53.469 --> 00:17:55.010
absorb that information,
you're going

00:17:55.010 --> 00:17:56.625
to know what the
best chefs know.

00:17:56.625 --> 00:17:58.250
And that will give
you a starting point

00:17:58.250 --> 00:17:59.180
in terms of knowledge.

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:01.912
In terms of skill,
you want to learn to--

00:18:01.912 --> 00:18:04.370
well, actually, one other thing
that's important with chefs

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:06.140
is the shopping aspect.

00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:09.800
This shopping is a
skill that if you

00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:12.290
aren't willing to invest in
the same level of ingredients

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:14.090
that the best chefs
work with, you're not

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:15.860
going to have the same results.

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:17.630
Sometimes the hardest
part is figuring

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:19.520
out-- where do you buy it?

00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:21.714
And chefs have already
done that hard work for you

00:18:21.714 --> 00:18:23.630
to find the very best
of the best ingredients.

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:26.030
We have a list of the
purveyors that provide chefs

00:18:26.030 --> 00:18:29.656
with some of the hard to find
ingredients, spices, herbs,

00:18:29.656 --> 00:18:30.155
seasonings.

00:18:30.155 --> 00:18:32.130
ANDREW DORNENBURG:
Lots of grains, too.

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:32.430
KAREN PAGE: Yes.

00:18:32.430 --> 00:18:34.596
ANDREW DORNENBURG: Yeah,
lots of grains and flowers.

00:18:34.596 --> 00:18:36.820
They all want their
polenta milled

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:40.050
a certain way or their
flour milled a certain way.

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:43.610
KAREN PAGE: So we've got a guide
to where to shop like a chef.

00:18:43.610 --> 00:18:45.560
And then in terms of
seasoning like a chef,

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:48.140
that's really what we were
talking about in "Culinary

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:49.790
Artistry" so many years ago.

00:18:49.790 --> 00:18:51.499
When we banished chefs
to a desert island

00:18:51.499 --> 00:18:53.956
and asked them to bring only
10 ingredients that they would

00:18:53.956 --> 00:18:55.520
cook with for the
rest of their life,

00:18:55.520 --> 00:18:57.170
the number one
ingredient was salt.

00:18:57.170 --> 00:18:59.650
And salt is really
the master technique.

00:18:59.650 --> 00:19:02.150
All the chefs in the room are
nodding their heads like, yes,

00:19:02.150 --> 00:19:03.490
of course.

00:19:03.490 --> 00:19:06.860
But to learn to add sodium to
a dish in a way that enhances

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:09.570
flavor without necessarily
adding flavor, which

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:12.470
we get into in the
alchemy stage of things,

00:19:12.470 --> 00:19:16.670
but it gets a little
more complicated.

00:19:16.670 --> 00:19:18.170
Above and beyond
"The Flavor Bible,"

00:19:18.170 --> 00:19:20.330
we talk about different
elements of salt. So not

00:19:20.330 --> 00:19:22.370
just which salt do
different chefs use--

00:19:22.370 --> 00:19:28.249
some use sea salt. Some use
mined salt. Some use pink salt.

00:19:28.249 --> 00:19:30.290
There are different salts
for different purposes.

00:19:30.290 --> 00:19:32.290
And thinking more
specifically about the salt

00:19:32.290 --> 00:19:36.110
you use, adding not only
sodium, but in some cases umami

00:19:36.110 --> 00:19:40.520
through a salty ingredient,
or other ingredients

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:43.970
that are complex, that will add
more than one taste at once.

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:46.070
If you learn how
to work with them,

00:19:46.070 --> 00:19:47.700
it can really
elevate your cooking.

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:50.490
We talked to one chef the
other night in New York City.

00:19:50.490 --> 00:19:51.206
We did an event.

00:19:51.206 --> 00:19:52.580
And he was talking
about the fact

00:19:52.580 --> 00:19:54.120
that he actually
ran out of salt,

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:56.150
which was the first
chef I've ever heard--

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:57.484
but it happens.

00:19:57.484 --> 00:19:58.150
We're all human.

00:19:58.150 --> 00:19:58.730
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: I've
never heard that before.

00:19:58.730 --> 00:20:00.180
ANDREW DORNENBURG: That's the
exact reaction everybody had.

00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:00.910
KAREN PAGE: I think
it was at home.

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:03.534
Maybe he wouldn't run out of it
at the restaurant, but at home.

00:20:03.534 --> 00:20:05.350
But he opened up his
refrigerator at home,

00:20:05.350 --> 00:20:06.558
and he had feta cheese there.

00:20:06.558 --> 00:20:09.290
So he took the liquid from
the feta, which is salty,

00:20:09.290 --> 00:20:11.930
and he used that as sort
of a liquid salt, ad hoc.

00:20:11.930 --> 00:20:13.722
And you know, it's just
one of those things

00:20:13.722 --> 00:20:15.180
that it's like,
well, of course you

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:16.370
could use salty ingredients.

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:17.810
It doesn't have to be salt.

00:20:17.810 --> 00:20:20.240
And I think part of what
"Kitchen Creativity" is all

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:23.294
about is how can you open your
mind to thinking not about

00:20:23.294 --> 00:20:24.710
specific ingredients,
but thinking

00:20:24.710 --> 00:20:26.840
about concepts that
you're adding to a dish

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:29.360
and to use it and really
extrapolate from there.

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:30.110
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: It's
interesting to think

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:31.970
through the whole aspect
of just seasoning,

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:33.860
because people think, oh, you
just add salt, and it's done.

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:35.777
Well, there's types of
salt. There's layering,

00:20:35.777 --> 00:20:37.276
when to add the
salt, when to add it

00:20:37.276 --> 00:20:38.990
in the beginning and
the end of cooking.

00:20:38.990 --> 00:20:41.448
And these are the tips that
are within the book that really

00:20:41.448 --> 00:20:43.250
help a good chef
become a great chef,

00:20:43.250 --> 00:20:45.666
and a great chef become an
excellent chef, whether, again,

00:20:45.666 --> 00:20:47.900
you're a home chef or not.

00:20:47.900 --> 00:20:50.240
So the first stage is mastery.

00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:53.060
And you made it very clear
that-- and all the chefs

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:55.550
said this in the book-- that
to be able to master anything,

00:20:55.550 --> 00:20:56.310
it's a lot of practice.

00:20:56.310 --> 00:20:57.351
It's a lot of discipline.

00:20:57.351 --> 00:20:58.760
It's a lot of time.

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:00.530
And once you
understand the rules,

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:02.697
then you can attempt
to break the rules.

00:21:02.697 --> 00:21:05.030
And then I think it kind of
takes you to that next step.

00:21:05.030 --> 00:21:06.510
So talk to them about
the next section,

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:08.468
which is around that
transformation and alchemy

00:21:08.468 --> 00:21:09.570
stage.

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:10.360
KAREN PAGE: Well,
that's the stage

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:12.360
that we've really been
writing about and talking

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:15.170
about for years now under
the guise of "Culinary

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:17.060
Artistry," "The Flavor
Bible," and "What to

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:18.200
Drink with What You Eat."

00:21:18.200 --> 00:21:20.990
So alchemy is really about, how
do you take something common

00:21:20.990 --> 00:21:23.120
and turn it into
something precious?

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:24.800
And what we mean by
that is that there

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:28.340
is a benefit in the culinary
world that one plus one

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:29.362
doesn't just equal two.

00:21:29.362 --> 00:21:31.070
There are instances
in which one plus one

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:33.330
can equal three or more.

00:21:33.330 --> 00:21:36.830
And what we have dedicated
our research to over the years

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:39.932
is trying to identify what is
the lock that you can put--

00:21:39.932 --> 00:21:42.140
the key that you can put
into the lock to really turn

00:21:42.140 --> 00:21:45.230
it to unlock the deliciousness
of particular ingredients,

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:47.870
whether they're herbs or
spices or other seasonings

00:21:47.870 --> 00:21:51.250
for specific ingredients.

00:21:51.250 --> 00:21:53.840
And this is what led us
both to sommelier school

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:57.350
is realizing that if you've
got a perfect plate of food

00:21:57.350 --> 00:21:59.895
in front of you, and you've got
the wrong wine in your glass,

00:21:59.895 --> 00:22:02.270
when you have the two together--
which you inevitably do,

00:22:02.270 --> 00:22:04.744
because you eat and drink
together-- it's going to clash.

00:22:04.744 --> 00:22:05.910
It's going to ruin the food.

00:22:05.910 --> 00:22:09.570
So we became committed to
studying wine and earning

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:11.760
our sommelier
certificates, because it

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:14.340
was so important to--

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:16.590
it was an important
way to master flavor.

00:22:16.590 --> 00:22:18.870
And that was the
best means that we

00:22:18.870 --> 00:22:20.880
had to be able to
train our palates

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:24.780
and to learn more about, well,
what was the secret to matching

00:22:24.780 --> 00:22:25.990
the best wines with food.

00:22:25.990 --> 00:22:28.380
And so we also interviewed
dozens of the best sommeliers

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:30.570
all across the
country, including

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:33.810
at some of the top restaurants
and people that you're

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:36.450
well acquainted with, and
really compiled that into "What

00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:38.400
to Drink With What
You Eat," which

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:41.160
is the ultimate food
and wine pairing guide,

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:42.600
because you can
look up the food.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:45.990
It will tell you what wine
or beer, spirits, cocktails,

00:22:45.990 --> 00:22:49.530
water, coffee, tea, et cetera
to drink with it to enhance

00:22:49.530 --> 00:22:50.952
the flavor of that food.

00:22:50.952 --> 00:22:53.160
Vice versa, if you're starting
with a bottle of wine,

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:54.618
you're starting
with a beer, you're

00:22:54.618 --> 00:22:56.640
starting with something
else, what food can you

00:22:56.640 --> 00:22:59.460
serve with it to best
enhance what's in the bottle

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:00.750
or what's in the glass?

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:03.270
And so when you bring all
of those elements together,

00:23:03.270 --> 00:23:05.880
that's really what we're talking
about in terms of alchemy.

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:08.370
If you master some of
the principles of-- what

00:23:08.370 --> 00:23:10.060
are the key flavor pairings?

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:11.384
What are the key--

00:23:11.384 --> 00:23:12.800
some of those
standard-- you know,

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:17.520
sancerre and oysters or
pinot noir and salmon.

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:19.410
If you master some
of those, it gets

00:23:19.410 --> 00:23:21.840
you so close to the ballpark
that you could actually

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:24.727
be only an OK chef with
a modicum of talent.

00:23:24.727 --> 00:23:26.310
But if you understand
those principles

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:28.080
and can apply them
in the kitchen,

00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:30.230
it's going to make you
shine to a whole new level.

00:23:30.230 --> 00:23:31.230
ANDREW DORNENBURG: Yeah.

00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:32.820
And we always talk about--

00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:35.600
think about what's in the
glass as a sauce, also.

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:38.880
And again, you know,
a really easy way

00:23:38.880 --> 00:23:41.280
to do that, a quick tool
is if it grows together,

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:42.484
it goes together.

00:23:42.484 --> 00:23:44.400
So if you're in Italy,
and you're making pasta

00:23:44.400 --> 00:23:48.000
from Northern Italy, see what
they drink in Northern Italy.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.340
If you're in the Bay Area,
and you're grilling a steak,

00:23:51.340 --> 00:23:52.905
well, gosh, grab
a bottle of zin.

00:23:52.905 --> 00:23:54.780
You know, they're right
there in Napa Valley.

00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:56.071
They're all next to each other.

00:23:56.071 --> 00:23:57.660
There's a natural synergy.

00:23:57.660 --> 00:23:59.070
But also, I think
it's also fun--

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:01.320
and just to wrap this
part up a little bit--

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:03.890
is that it's not just wine.

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:06.914
You can have a lemon
soda with a salad,

00:24:06.914 --> 00:24:09.080
and that could almost be
your dressing on the salad.

00:24:09.080 --> 00:24:10.610
So you think outside--

00:24:10.610 --> 00:24:12.310
just think of the
classic pairings,

00:24:12.310 --> 00:24:15.120
and we all know that
you can actually drink

00:24:15.120 --> 00:24:16.770
white wine with many things.

00:24:16.770 --> 00:24:19.050
You can actually drink
red wine with fish now.

00:24:19.050 --> 00:24:19.930
It's OK.

00:24:19.930 --> 00:24:21.270
Pinot noir and salmon.

00:24:21.270 --> 00:24:25.440
So think of all the beverages
with what you can bring in.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:28.590
And again, that's going to
change a lot of your meals

00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:30.900
just by having the
proper beverage.

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:31.480
You know?

00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:33.212
That's the three there.

00:24:33.212 --> 00:24:35.670
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: I think
you hit on a lot of key points,

00:24:35.670 --> 00:24:38.700
and it goes much deeper than
just the actual dishes itself.

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:40.890
It goes to what's being
paired, your surroundings,

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:43.410
and it creates that
experience that if any of you

00:24:43.410 --> 00:24:46.230
think about your most
epic food experience

00:24:46.230 --> 00:24:48.480
you've ever had-- it could
be a hot dog at a ballpark,

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:50.390
it could be at a Michelin
star restaurant--

00:24:50.390 --> 00:24:52.470
there's different things
that all came together.

00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:55.800
And a great culinarian
makes that look so easy.

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:58.430
And a lot of these
tips are in the book.

00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:00.870
And so it's super exciting.

00:25:00.870 --> 00:25:02.400
There's a great
quote in the book,

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:06.640
and it starts off by saying
to not copy other chefs.

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:09.990
But to be able to get
inspired, I and many others

00:25:09.990 --> 00:25:13.614
feel that copying is actually
the gateway to get into.

00:25:13.614 --> 00:25:14.530
Can you speak to that?

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:15.880
Because it's kind
of a contradiction,

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:17.130
but it actually
makes total sense.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:18.546
KAREN PAGE: Yes,
well, that's sort

00:25:18.546 --> 00:25:21.900
of the hook in the
beginning of the book

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:24.150
is talking about-- we want
to teach you creativity.

00:25:24.150 --> 00:25:25.800
What's the definition
of creativity?

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:28.350
It's not copying, coming
up with something that's

00:25:28.350 --> 00:25:32.580
new and useful and surprising.

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:34.800
And yet by
definition, how do you

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:36.570
get to that point of
being able to do it?

00:25:36.570 --> 00:25:37.550
You need to learn the rules.

00:25:37.550 --> 00:25:38.675
How do you learn the rules?

00:25:38.675 --> 00:25:39.420
You copy.

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:41.460
So that's the push me, pull you.

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:44.354
And I think that
that is a lesson that

00:25:44.354 --> 00:25:46.770
comes through time and time
again in the book in that it's

00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.100
never one or the other.

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:49.920
It's never hot versus cold.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:52.165
It's both.

00:25:52.165 --> 00:25:53.790
In the back of the
book under Y, you'll

00:25:53.790 --> 00:25:55.920
find "yes, and" being
one of the key rules

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:57.960
that you need to
master for creativity.

00:25:57.960 --> 00:26:00.660
And it's the first
rule of improvisation.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:03.030
If you've ever done any
improvisational acting,

00:26:03.030 --> 00:26:06.090
you know that if someone
says something like, OK,

00:26:06.090 --> 00:26:07.590
here's the premise
of this scene.

00:26:07.590 --> 00:26:10.537
I'm going to walk in, and I
dropped the book on the floor.

00:26:10.537 --> 00:26:12.870
You don't say, oh, no, no,
no, you didn't drop the book.

00:26:12.870 --> 00:26:14.820
You have to say, yes,
you dropped the book,

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:17.449
and that was the book
that I was on the waitlist

00:26:17.449 --> 00:26:18.240
for at the library.

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:21.270
It's like, yes, and
that was the book

00:26:21.270 --> 00:26:24.720
that my ex-boyfriend
actually wrote.

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:27.150
And you add onto the story.

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:29.850
So you always add on to
it, because you never

00:26:29.850 --> 00:26:31.330
want to break that chain.

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:34.470
So the key that you can take
from the improvisational rules

00:26:34.470 --> 00:26:37.020
and to apply in the kitchen
is no matter what happens,

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:38.940
you trust that it's
there to serve you,

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:40.220
and it's for a reason.

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:42.720
And what we tell people
is it kind of goes--

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:44.910
if you look in the
beginning of the book,

00:26:44.910 --> 00:26:48.030
there's a list of
different classic dishes

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:49.710
and what their origins were.

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:52.120
And a lot of times,
they came from mistakes.

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:53.850
So there was something
that went wrong.

00:26:53.850 --> 00:26:56.910
The burrito gets knocked
into the deep fat fryer.

00:26:56.910 --> 00:26:58.290
Hey, chimichangas.

00:26:58.290 --> 00:27:01.180
Or the ravioli gets knocked
into the deep fat fryer.

00:27:01.180 --> 00:27:03.280
Hey, toasted ravioli
turns into a thing.

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:04.150
People love it.

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:08.250
So things are never really
mistakes if you pay attention

00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:08.750
to it.

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:11.190
And so at Craftsman and
Wolves in San Francisco,

00:27:11.190 --> 00:27:14.560
the intern undercooks the
egg that you asked her

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:15.880
to hard boil.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:16.710
It's soft boiled.

00:27:16.710 --> 00:27:17.800
It oozes out.

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:18.430
Wait a second.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:19.434
That's kind of cool.

00:27:19.434 --> 00:27:21.100
And you find out that
people love things

00:27:21.100 --> 00:27:22.270
that ooze out of other things.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:23.650
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: You
just let all the secrets out

00:27:23.650 --> 00:27:24.800
of our mistakes.

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:26.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:26.410 --> 00:27:27.100
Thanks, Karen.

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:28.220
KAREN PAGE: There
are no mistakes.

00:27:28.220 --> 00:27:28.920
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: It's
a really good point.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:31.330
I think Ferran Adria talks
in the book about the fact

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:33.960
that if you're
unique, and if you're

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:36.460
doing something innovative that
no one else has done before,

00:27:36.460 --> 00:27:37.760
and you're not
copying, then no one

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:39.510
can really judge it
against anything else.

00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:40.900
And I think that's a good point.

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:43.330
But you cannot go that
direction unless you've got

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:45.550
the understanding of the
technique and the mastery

00:27:45.550 --> 00:27:46.187
to begin with.

00:27:46.187 --> 00:27:48.520
And obviously, Ferran is one
of the most acclaimed chefs

00:27:48.520 --> 00:27:50.440
out there, and so he can
easily pull that off.

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:51.856
But I think it's
a great testament

00:27:51.856 --> 00:27:54.340
to get inspired by seeing
what other people do,

00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:55.810
have conversations.

00:27:55.810 --> 00:27:58.057
Whatever your inspiration
is to document it.

00:27:58.057 --> 00:27:59.890
And you have a lot of
great tips in the book

00:27:59.890 --> 00:28:03.010
around, how do you capture
that moment of creativity?

00:28:03.010 --> 00:28:04.510
It's about always
being positive.

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:06.470
It's about surrounding
yourself with others

00:28:06.470 --> 00:28:07.450
on great conversations.

00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:08.741
It's about writing things down.

00:28:08.741 --> 00:28:11.080
And you know, most
chefs, great chefs,

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:12.580
have either a pocketbook--

00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:12.850
KAREN PAGE: A notebook.

00:28:12.850 --> 00:28:13.300
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: --a pen--

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:13.640
