00:49:13.603 --> 00:49:15.960
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
how you approach--

00:49:15.960 --> 00:49:17.470
ANDREW DORNENBURG: So what's
the entire process like?

00:49:17.470 --> 00:49:19.060
KAREN PAGE: What's the
entire process when it comes

00:49:19.060 --> 00:49:20.590
to the research for our books?

00:49:20.590 --> 00:49:22.450
And this one in particular--

00:49:22.450 --> 00:49:24.940
for this book, we
had both a bottom-up

00:49:24.940 --> 00:49:27.280
and a top-down approach,
where the bottom-up approach

00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:31.480
was basically talking to
chefs about what they felt

00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:34.030
was important to know about
their creative process,

00:49:34.030 --> 00:49:35.320
about how they cooked.

00:49:35.320 --> 00:49:37.300
And all of them have
different specialties.

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:41.020
Some of them have different
countries that they specialize

00:49:41.020 --> 00:49:43.710
or different techniques that
they specialize in, something

00:49:43.710 --> 00:49:46.990
that roots their cuisine and
makes it different from anyone

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:47.770
else's.

00:49:47.770 --> 00:49:50.350
And so we wanted to
understand, from talking

00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:54.580
to Kyle Connaughton, a single
thread about his influences

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:58.660
in working in Japan and
that Japanese sensibility

00:49:58.660 --> 00:50:03.220
that he brings to his food in
conjunction to the crazy stuff

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:06.580
that he's doing with
Heston Blumenthal

00:50:06.580 --> 00:50:10.690
and that he'd learned at El
Bulli, working at El Bulli.

00:50:10.690 --> 00:50:12.464
So he sort of brings
it all together

00:50:12.464 --> 00:50:13.630
in a really interesting way.

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:16.680
Other people like Rick Bayless
from Frontera Grill in Chicago

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:19.360
is much more specialized
in Mexican cuisine.

00:50:19.360 --> 00:50:21.130
And so we wanted to
really understand that

00:50:21.130 --> 00:50:22.060
by talking to Rick.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:24.550
We talked to his
chef de cuisine.

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:26.920
And we really wanted to
understand their approach

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:28.360
to thinking about things.

00:50:28.360 --> 00:50:30.520
And the beautiful
thing about it is

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:34.600
that when you talk to people who
are the best at what they do,

00:50:34.600 --> 00:50:36.880
they've been doing it, in
some cases, for decades.

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:40.110
And that creativity is
reflected in an evolution

00:50:40.110 --> 00:50:43.090
that their cuisine goes through,
the evolution of their thought

00:50:43.090 --> 00:50:45.650
process, where they're
designing a new menu

00:50:45.650 --> 00:50:48.160
and had brainstormed
a list of adjectives

00:50:48.160 --> 00:50:50.320
that best described
certain dishes.

00:50:50.320 --> 00:50:53.860
So they organize their menu
not by appetizer, entree,

00:50:53.860 --> 00:50:56.750
and dessert, but
by characteristic.

00:50:56.750 --> 00:50:59.890
So it shows the level of thought
process that they put into it.

00:50:59.890 --> 00:51:03.610
They also use inspiration
by different paintings

00:51:03.610 --> 00:51:05.570
and different works of
art in their restaurant.

00:51:05.570 --> 00:51:08.260
They will come up with dishes
that are a reflection of that.

00:51:08.260 --> 00:51:12.880
So the research is extensive
in terms of speaking to chefs.

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:16.990
We also do extensive research
on restaurant reviews,

00:51:16.990 --> 00:51:19.060
trying to understand
their restaurants

00:51:19.060 --> 00:51:21.590
from a local
critic's perspective.

00:51:21.590 --> 00:51:22.760
We review their cookbooks.

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:25.980
We review their menus.

00:51:25.980 --> 00:51:29.780
And then we kind of put it
all together and kind of

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:30.960
bring it all together.

00:51:30.960 --> 00:51:35.060
We also studied
creativity from the point

00:51:35.060 --> 00:51:37.120
of view of various
experts on creativity.

00:51:37.120 --> 00:51:39.985
So we spoke to experts like
Michael Gelb, the author

00:51:39.985 --> 00:51:41.360
of "How to Think
Like Leonardo da

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:44.920
Vinci," and "The
Art of Connection"

00:51:44.920 --> 00:51:49.147
on how do you really bring
those elements of creativity?

00:51:49.147 --> 00:51:51.230
What are the things that
we should be looking for?

00:51:51.230 --> 00:51:54.530
And he has identified some
of the key genius thinking

00:51:54.530 --> 00:51:56.210
attributes of Leonardo da Vinci.

00:51:56.210 --> 00:51:58.910
We saw them in the world's
most creative chefs.

00:51:58.910 --> 00:52:02.690
And so I think through that
opportunity of really bringing

00:52:02.690 --> 00:52:04.910
the two together,
we saw how chefs

00:52:04.910 --> 00:52:07.070
were the perfect
exemplars of some

00:52:07.070 --> 00:52:10.070
of the best creativity that's
going on in the world today.

00:52:10.070 --> 00:52:12.860
And to really take a look
at their best practices

00:52:12.860 --> 00:52:15.660
and really try to
translate that for anyone,

00:52:15.660 --> 00:52:18.980
whether it's a professional
chef or a home cook,

00:52:18.980 --> 00:52:22.160
to help you to be more
creative when you least feel

00:52:22.160 --> 00:52:24.271
the inspiration to be creative.

00:52:24.271 --> 00:52:25.520
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: Excellent.

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:28.370
So we have one or
two more questions.

00:52:28.370 --> 00:52:30.620
So one thing that I'm
taking away from this,

00:52:30.620 --> 00:52:32.830
and I'm hoping you are
as well, is the thought

00:52:32.830 --> 00:52:34.940
and intentionality,
depending on whoever

00:52:34.940 --> 00:52:37.430
you are that's creating
something, is immense.

00:52:37.430 --> 00:52:39.960
And when you are preparing
your next meal or when

00:52:39.960 --> 00:52:40.960
you're at a restaurant--

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:42.650
I would say when you're
preparing your own meal

00:52:42.650 --> 00:52:44.108
or someone else is
cooking for you,

00:52:44.108 --> 00:52:46.280
specifically at home,
turn off the TV.

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:47.780
You know, turn off
the distractions.

00:52:47.780 --> 00:52:51.410
And take a few minutes to really
be mindful of the experience

00:52:51.410 --> 00:52:53.000
that someone else
has prepared for you

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:54.110
or that you've
prepared for yourself.

00:52:54.110 --> 00:52:55.820
And the reason I mention
that-- and this is in the book

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:56.630
as well--

00:52:56.630 --> 00:53:00.200
is music and other
distractions can either enhance

00:53:00.200 --> 00:53:03.170
or completely detract
from the experience.

00:53:03.170 --> 00:53:05.600
And knowing the
thought that went

00:53:05.600 --> 00:53:08.360
into just something
as simple as a salad,

00:53:08.360 --> 00:53:10.020
and it's just not
a simple dish--

00:53:10.020 --> 00:53:11.394
and it was delicious,
by the way.

00:53:11.394 --> 00:53:12.370
That roasted mushroom?

00:53:12.370 --> 00:53:12.680
DEDE SAMPSON: Right?

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:13.180
Yes.

00:53:13.180 --> 00:53:16.270
SCOTT GIAMBASTIANI: That
was like the winning hook

00:53:16.270 --> 00:53:18.860
there that got me to go for
the next bite was the mushroom.

00:53:18.860 --> 00:53:20.882
But think about that as
you're creating things.

00:53:20.882 --> 00:53:22.340
And have a conversation
with people

00:53:22.340 --> 00:53:23.615
when you're cooking
for them, because this

00:53:23.615 --> 00:53:24.750
is what it's all about.

00:53:24.750 --> 00:53:26.583
And the reason I mention
turning down the TV

00:53:26.583 --> 00:53:29.130
is it's so easy just to be
mindless and just, you know,

00:53:29.130 --> 00:53:30.347
it's not dining anymore.

00:53:30.347 --> 00:53:31.430
It's just kind of feeding.

00:53:31.430 --> 00:53:32.860
And we all do that at times.

00:53:32.860 --> 00:53:35.840
But thank you for all the
work that you've done here.

00:53:35.840 --> 00:53:37.400
Was there another
couple questions

00:53:37.400 --> 00:53:39.260
before we line up
