00:53:39.260 --> 00:53:40.137
Yes.

00:53:40.137 --> 00:53:41.512
AUDIENCE: Holidays
are coming up,

00:53:41.512 --> 00:53:44.893
and we have some big,
very traditional meals.

00:53:44.893 --> 00:53:47.308
Do you have any advice for
how to inject creativity

00:53:47.308 --> 00:53:48.760
into those occasions?

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:50.080
KAREN PAGE: Great question.

00:53:50.080 --> 00:53:52.900
You know, a lot of times
it's very personal.

00:53:52.900 --> 00:53:55.360
The holidays are times that
we typically get together

00:53:55.360 --> 00:53:57.610
with family or
friends, loved ones,

00:53:57.610 --> 00:54:00.350
and there's a lot of childhood
memories that are involved.

00:54:00.350 --> 00:54:02.500
Andrew and I, our families
had different stuffings

00:54:02.500 --> 00:54:03.499
when we were growing up.

00:54:03.499 --> 00:54:06.460
So now we have a multiple
stuffing celebration

00:54:06.460 --> 00:54:08.050
this time of year.

00:54:08.050 --> 00:54:10.572
But a lot of times, you
know, there's a sacredness.

00:54:10.572 --> 00:54:11.530
You don't always want--

00:54:11.530 --> 00:54:13.840
creativity isn't
always a good thing.

00:54:13.840 --> 00:54:16.100
Daniel Ballou says if
you're making steak frites,

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:17.260
you let it be steak frites.

00:54:17.260 --> 00:54:19.620
You don't want to get
too creative with that.

00:54:19.620 --> 00:54:23.320
Sometimes there is sacred
cows or sacred turkeys

00:54:23.320 --> 00:54:25.261
when it comes to
Thanksgiving that you

00:54:25.261 --> 00:54:26.260
don't want to mess with.

00:54:26.260 --> 00:54:27.926
If you want to have
a happy Thanksgiving

00:54:27.926 --> 00:54:30.010
and have it be as
peaceful and calm around

00:54:30.010 --> 00:54:31.420
the table as possible,
you don't want to mess

00:54:31.420 --> 00:54:32.670
with people's favorite dishes.

00:54:32.670 --> 00:54:34.270
But there are times
that you can take

00:54:34.270 --> 00:54:37.120
what the essence
of Thanksgiving is,

00:54:37.120 --> 00:54:41.640
and if you can deconstruct, what
is it that's important to you?

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:44.060
Well, I want to have a
pumpkin dessert on the table.

00:54:44.060 --> 00:54:45.810
It doesn't have
to be pumpkin pie.

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:46.940
And then you can
start playing with it.

00:54:46.940 --> 00:54:48.440
OK, am I going to
do a pumpkin tart?

00:54:48.440 --> 00:54:50.680
Am I going to do
a pumpkin ravioli?

00:54:50.680 --> 00:54:52.390
Am I going to make
it a side dish?

00:54:52.390 --> 00:54:53.660
You know, how am I
going to play with that?

00:54:53.660 --> 00:54:55.660
Am I going to come up
with a pumpkin cocktail?

00:54:55.660 --> 00:54:57.400
So you can have--
you know, there's

00:54:57.400 --> 00:55:03.130
a place in New York City where
we had a turkey sandwich that

00:55:03.130 --> 00:55:06.260
was served with a bag
of sweet potato chips

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:09.482
and a cranberry fizzy drink.

00:55:09.482 --> 00:55:11.440
And you realize all the
flavors of Thanksgiving

00:55:11.440 --> 00:55:14.023
are right there, but they're in
a completely different format.

00:55:14.023 --> 00:55:14.954
If you can take the--

00:55:14.954 --> 00:55:16.870
figure it out, you know,
do the deconstruction

00:55:16.870 --> 00:55:20.130
of what are the flavors
that mean Christmas to you

00:55:20.130 --> 00:55:22.900
or Hanukkah to you or
Thanksgiving to you

00:55:22.900 --> 00:55:24.010
and narrow them down.

00:55:24.010 --> 00:55:26.051
And it's like, OK, well,
I have to have stuffing,

00:55:26.051 --> 00:55:28.710
or I have to have gravy,
or whatever your thing is--

00:55:28.710 --> 00:55:29.210
sorry?

